ThinkPart(
    type='think',
    think="This is very informative. Looking at the auth service:\n\n1. `getMe` 
returns `is_new_user = !user.profile || !user.profile.is_complete`\n2. The auth 
bloc checks `isNewUser || !profileComplete` to redirect to profile-setup\n3. The
seed script creates 10 users with phone numbers `13800000000` to `13800000009`, 
all with complete profiles\n4. The E2E test phone is `13800138000`, which is NOT
in the seed data\n\nSo when `13800138000` logs in:\n- `findOrCreateUser` creates
a NEW user with `is_complete: false` profile\n- `getMe` returns `is_new_user: tr
ue, profile_complete: false`\n- The app redirects to `/profile-setup`\n\nThis me
ans the test user `13800138000` will ALWAYS have an incomplete profile (unless t
he profile setup flow completes it). But the profile setup flow will complete th
e profile, and then subsequent matching flows will find the user has a complete 
profile.\n\nWait, but the matching flows also use `clearState: true` and then lo
gin again. Since the test user `13800138000` might have been used before and com
pleted their profile, the next time they log in, `is_new_user` would be `false` 
but `profile_complete` would be `true` (if the profile was saved). Then the app 
would redirect to `/home`.\n\nBut looking at `findOrCreateUser`:\n```ts\nlet use
r = await this.userRepo.findOne({ where: { phone } });\n```\n\nIf the user was c
reated in a previous test run, they would exist. And if their profile was comple
ted, `is_complete` would be true.\n\nSo the state depends on whether the test us
er already exists and has a complete profile. Since we're in an E2E environment,
we need to be careful about test isolation.\n\nFor the matching flows to work re
liably, we might need to ensure the test user has a complete profile. The profil
e setup flow could be run first to create and complete the profile, but then we 
need to make sure subsequent matching flows work.\n\nActually, looking at the ma
tching flows:\n- `swipe_recommendations.yaml`: logs in, expects to be on home pa
ge\n- `view_match_list.yaml`: logs in, taps on messages tab\n\nIf the test user 
already has a complete profile (from previous runs), these flows will work becau
se after login the app goes to `/home`.\n\nIf the test user does NOT have a comp
lete profile, the app will redirect to `/profile-setup`, and the matching flows 
will fail because they expect to see `mode_tab_nearby` or be able to tap `tab_me
ssages`.\n\nFor a clean E2E run, we should probably:\n1. Run profile setup first
to ensure the test user has a complete profile\n2. Then run matching flows\n\nBU
T if profile setup has already been run before, the user already exists with a c
omplete profile, and running profile setup again would fail because the app goes
to `/home` instead of `/profile-setup`.\n\nHmm, this is a tricky state managemen
t issue for E2E tests.\n\nOne solution: the matching flows should not assume the
user has a complete profile. But the PRD says incomplete profiles should block m
atching. So the matching flows need a user with a complete profile.\n\nAnother s
olution: clear the database between runs, or use `clearState: true` in the app a
nd have a backend endpoint to reset the test user.\n\nActually, looking at the s
eed script, it truncates all tables and re-seeds. Maybe the E2E environment is s
upposed to be reset before each run. But we don't have control over that.\n\nFor
the purpose of this task, let me just run the tests and see what happens. The mo
st important thing is to identify what's broken and fix the flows.\n\nLet me als
o check if there's a `make e2e-env-up` command that seeds the database.",
    encrypted=None
)
